definition.value: Any trans-3-enoyl-CoA(4-) that is also saturated at position 4.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 2-oxoundec-10-en-1-yl group.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 16-hydroxy-2-oxohexadecyl group.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 3-methyl-2-oxoheptadecyl group.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 4-methyl-2-oxododecyl group.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 13-methyl-2-oxononadecyl group.
An acyl tetraketide pyran-2-one that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a 13-methyl-2-oxotetradecyl group.
A member of the class of  triazoles that is 1-phenyl-1H-1,2,4-triazole substituted by 2-hydroxyphenyl groups at positions 3 and 5.
An alpha-amino acid residue derived from N(4)-(beta-D-glucosyl)-L-asparagine.
An indolecarboxylate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3-methyl-2-indolic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

An iron coordination entity consisting of two carbonyl and one cyano group coordinated to a central iron atom. The product of HydG, which is then passed onto HydE and HydF to form the H-cluster of the [FeFe]-hydrogenase enzymes.
A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2,6-dimethylheptanoic acid.
An aromatic ether that is aniline in which the hydrogen at position 4 is replaced by an ethoxy group. It is a hydrolysis metabolite of phenacetin.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (11Z)-18-hydroxyoctadecenoic acid.
A GDP-D-mannuronic acid in which the anomeric centre of the mannuronic acid fragment has alpha-configuration.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (9Z,12Z)-18-hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid.

A dicarboxylic acid diamide consisting of 3-aminoalanine in which the alpha-amino fuunction is acylated by a 3-carbamoyloxirane-2-carbonyl group. NB Although the relative configuration of the epoxide moiety has been assigned as trans, it has not yet been established whether the absolute configuration is R,R (as drawn) or S,S.
A hydroxy fatty acid comprising lauric acid carrying a single hydroxy substituent at position 7.
Any member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 4-hydroxy-6-methyl-2H-pyran-2-one in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group has been replaced by an acyl group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the 5-amino group of 5-amino-5-(4-hydroxybenzyl)-6-((2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentyl)amino)dihydropyrimidine-2,4-dione.
Any member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 4-hydroxy-2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 has been replaced by an alkyl group.
A member of the class of pteridines that is pteridine in which the hydrogens at positions 2, 4, and 7 have been replaced by hydroxy groups.

A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of eight deoxyadenosine, four thymidine, three deoxycytidine and seven deoxyguanosine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence ATGGACCAAAGAGTTTCAGGGA. It is a mimic of HuR mRNA nucleotides 671-692 and acts as an antagonist that deregulates human antigen R (HuR) expression and inhibits AKT(SER473) phosphorylation in prostate and other cancers.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine where the acyl group specified is glutaconyl.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine that is L-carnitine having a hydroxyhexanoyl group as the acyl substituent in which the position of the hydroxy group is unspecified.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine compound having trans-2-methyl-2-butenoyl (tiglyl) as the acyl substituent.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 5-phosphate in which both phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl).
An O-acyl-L-carnitine that is L-carnitine having a 3-methylglutaryl group as the acyl substituent
An O-acyl-L-carnitine in which the acyl group specified is hexenoyl in which the position of the double bond is unspecified.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (3E,5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosapentaenoic acid.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine that is L-carnitine having a pimelyl group as the acyl substituent.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine that is L-carnitine having a octenoyl group as the acyl substituent in which the position of the double bond is unspecified.
The L-enantiomer of  O-nonanoylcarnitine.
An acyl-CoA thioester that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-(methylthio)acrylic acid.
An acyl-CoA thioester that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-hydroxy-3-(methylthio)propanoic acid.
A secondary amino compound that is spermidine in which each of the primary amino groups has been mono-acylated by formal condensation with trans-coumaric acid.
A 4-coumaroyl-CoA in which the double bond of the coumaroyl group has trans-geochemistry.
A delta-lactone that is D-galactono-1,4-lactone in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
An amino-acid betaine that is trans-4-hydroxy-L-proline zwitterion in which both of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen have been replaced by methyl groups.
An amino-acid betaine that is trans-4-hydroxy-D-proline zwitterion in which both of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen have been replaced by methyl groups.
A doubly-charged N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of N-succinyl-L-alpha-amino acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
An arenesulfonic acid that is guaiacol sulfated at position 4. Commonly used (in the form of its potassium salt) as an expectorant.
A (2-chloro-5-oxo-2,5-dihydro-2-furyl)acetate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of (R)-(2-chloro-5-oxo-2,5-dihydro-2-furyl)acetic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An arenesulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group of 4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzene-1-sulfonic acid.
An antagonist that binds to and deactivates thromboxane A2 receptors.
